I now have the complete picture from the knowledge graph. Here is the full diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The cap-height of your serif glyphs is being cropped at the top edge of the `<input>` element. Increasing `padding-top` makes the input box taller but **does not move the text** — the glyphs still sit flush against the internal top of the text rendering area. This is not a padding problem. It is a **line-height / browser native text rendering problem** specific to `<input>` at display scale.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-064 · EAP-077**

The `<input>` element is a **replaced element with a UA-controlled internal text layout**. It has three layered behaviours that interact catastrophically at display scale with a serif font like IBM Plex Serif:

### 1. `line-height: normal` resolves differently inside `<input>` than outside it

Browsers compute `normal` line-height as roughly `1.0–1.2 × font-size` for most fonts. For a sans-serif UI font at 16 px, the cap-height is ~70% of the em-square, so the natural line-height of ~1.2 leaves enough room. **IBM Plex Serif at display scale (36–60 px) has a much taller cap-height relative to the em-square**, and browsers do not guarantee that `line-height: normal` inside an `<input>` allocates enough space for the ascender + cap-height together. The browser's native text renderer clips the glyph outline **at the edge of the computed line box**, which sits at the very top edge of the input's content area.

### 2. `padding-top` only affects the box — not the line box position

The browser positions the single-line `<input>` text by centering it vertically in the content box using an internal algorithm, not by respecting the CSS `padding-top` you set. Increasing `padding-top` shifts the box boundary downward and makes the element taller, but the text rendering origin is still the same relative position inside the content area. The top glyph still clips.

### 3. `<input>` creates a browser-managed stacking context for text

The UA stylesheet applies `-webkit-appearance: none` internals and its own text-rendering path. The text lives in a browser-native text renderer that is **not subject to CSS `overflow: visible`**, so you cannot simply let the line box overflow the element bounds to save the ascenders.

The combination: font-size is large → cap-height is large → line-height: normal is not large enough → ascender/cap-height protrudes above the line box top → browser clips at the element boundary. No amount of padding CSS fixes this because padding and text layout are independent at the UA level. This is **EAP-077** verbatim: *"Assuming CSS Can Fix `<input>` Native Text Clipping for Oversized Serif Fonts."*

---

## Fix

The canonical solution (established via FB-129 / ENG-139, used on the login page) is to **replace `<input>` with a `contenteditable` div that mimics input semantics.** The `contenteditable` div uses the normal document text renderer, where `line-height` and padding behave predictably and glyph overflow is controllable.

### Step 1 — Replace the `<input>` with a `contenteditable` div

The component is almost certainly in:

```
src/components/admin/editors/DisplayTitleInput.tsx
```
(or wherever your case-study editor renders the display-scale title field — look for the component that applies `heading-case-study-intro` or a display-scale serif mixin to an `<input>`.)

**Before:**
```tsx
// DisplayTitleInput.tsx
<input
  type="text"
  className={styles.titleInput}
  value={value}
  onChange={(e) => onChange(e.target.value)}
  placeholder="Case study title"
/>
```

**After:**
```tsx
// DisplayTitleInput.tsx
import { useRef, useEffect } from 'react'

interface DisplayTitleInputProps {
  value: string
  onChange: (value: string) => void
  placeholder?: string
}

export function DisplayTitleInput({
  value,
  onChange,
  placeholder = 'Case study title',
}: DisplayTitleInputProps) {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

  // Sync external value → DOM (only when the div doesn't already have that text,
  // to avoid clobbering the cursor position mid-type)
  useEffect(() => {
    const el = ref.current
    if (!el) return
    if (el.textContent !== value) {
      el.textContent = value
    }
  }, [value])

  return (
    <div
      ref={ref}
      role="textbox"
      aria-label="Case study display title"
      aria-multiline="false"
      contentEditable
      suppressContentEditableWarning
      data-placeholder={placeholder}
      className={styles.titleInput}
      onInput={(e) => {
        onChange((e.currentTarget as HTMLDivElement).textContent ?? '')
      }}
      onKeyDown={(e) => {
        // Prevent newlines — this is a single-line title field
        if (e.key === 'Enter') {
          e.preventDefault()
        }
      }}
      onPaste={(e) => {
        // Strip rich text on paste — plain text only
        e.preventDefault()
        const text = e.clipboardData.getData('text/plain')
        document.execCommand('insertText', false, text)
      }}
    />
  )
}
```

### Step 2 — Update the SCSS module

The glyph-safe rules are:

```scss
// DisplayTitleInput.module.scss

.titleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro; // IBM Plex Serif, fluid 36–60px, weight 500, leading 1.25

  display: block;
  width: 100%;

  // ─── Glyph-safe vertical space ───────────────────────────────────────────
  // IBM Plex Serif at display scale has cap-height ≈ 73% of the em-square and
  // ascenders that reach nearly 90%. At 60px, the ascender is ~54px.
  // line-height: 1.25 gives 75px of line box — just enough, but cap glyphs like
  // 'T', 'H', 'É' sit at the very top of that line box with zero clearance.
  // Add explicit top/bottom padding ON THE CONTENTEDITABLE DIV (not an input)
  // so the glyph ink never touches the box boundary.
  padding-block: $portfolio-spacer-1x; // 8px top + bottom — safe for the ascender
  padding-inline: 0;                   // let the parent column control horizontal rhythm

  // ─── Input appearance ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  background: transparent;
  border: none;
  outline: none;
  color: inherit;
  cursor: text;
  white-space: nowrap;      // single-line semantics
  overflow: hidden;         // ← See Note below
  text-overflow: ellipsis;

  // ─── Placeholder via data-attribute (inputs use ::placeholder; 
  //     contenteditable uses :empty + data-placeholder + ::before) ──────────
  &:empty::before {
    content: attr(data-placeholder);
    color: $portfolio-color-text-tertiary;
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  // ─── Focus ring (replaces the native input outline) ──────────────────────
  &:focus-within,
  &:focus {
    outline: none;
    // Use the same box-shadow ring established by AP-054
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px $portfolio-color-border-focus;
  }
}
```

> **⚠️ Note on `overflow: hidden` with `contenteditable`** (EAP-080): `overflow: hidden` on a `contenteditable` container *is* safe here because the clip happens on the **horizontal** axis for text that overflows the field width — not on the vertical axis. The `padding-block: $portfolio-spacer-1x` ensures 8px of clearance above the cap-height before the box boundary, so vertical glyph ink never reaches the clipping edge. If you later see vertical clipping return after reducing padding, increase `padding-block-start` specifically — ascenders need more room than descenders at display scale.

### Step 3 — If `overflow: hidden` ever clips tall glyphs again

The correct expansion formula for display-scale IBM Plex Serif:

```
required padding-block-start = (line-height × font-size) - (cap-height × font-size)
                              = (1.25 × 60px) - (0.73 × 60px)
                              = 75px - 43.8px
                              = 31.2px theoretical line box headroom
```

In practice you need at minimum the **ascender overshoot**: `(ascender_units / UPM) × font-size`. For IBM Plex Serif, ascender ≈ 820/1000 UPM → `0.82 × 60px = 49.2px`. The line box is `75px`, so there are `75 - 49.2 = 25.8px` of clearance — sufficient for padding-block-start of 8px. If the font-size is ever below ~36px, clearance shrinks to `< 10px` and you should increase `padding-block-start` to `$portfolio-spacer-1-5x` (12px).

---

## Why This Is Structurally Different for Display-Scale Fonts

Here is the complete taxonomy of what changes at display scale:

| Property | Body scale (14–18 px) | Display scale (36–60 px) |
|---|---|---|
| **Glyph ink vs em-square** | Ink fits comfortably inside the em-square with room to spare | Ink fills the em-square; serifs and ascenders approach or touch its edge |
| **Cap-height as % of line box** | ~55–60% of line box (line-height ≥ 1.4 gives big buffers) | ~73–80% of line box (line-height of 1.25 leaves only 25% for clearance above+below) |
| **`<input>` vertical centering** | UA centering error is invisible — the error (±1–2px) is smaller than the clearance buffer | UA centering error is visible and damaging — a 2px misalignment at 60px font-size clips the cap |
| **`line-height: normal` resolution** | Resolves to ~1.15–1.2, gives ~4–5px clearance above cap-height | Resolves to ~1.0–1.1 in many UA stylesheets, gives ≤0px clearance |
| **Ascender height** | Ascenders rarely exceed the cap-height visually | IBM Plex Serif ascenders on 'd', 'f', 'k', 'h' at 60px are taller than cap-height (≈820/1000 UPM vs 700/1000 cap) |
| **CSS `padding-top` effectiveness on `<input>`** | Works — at small sizes UA centering rarely interferes | **Does not work** — UA positions the text independently of padding |
| **`contenteditable` div** | Works, but overkill — `<input>` is fine at body scale | **Required** — the only way to get document-flow text rendering at display scale |

The core insight: at body scale the glyph is small relative to the line box so all the rounding errors and UA quirks are invisible. At display scale every pixel matters — the glyph is nearly as tall as its container and the browser's internal text layout machinery works against you.

---

## Principle

**EAP-077 · AP-064:** Never use a native `<input>` element for display-scale serif text. The browser's UA text layout inside `<input>` elements is not governed by the same rules as block-level document text flow. At font sizes above ~24px with a serif font, ascender/cap-height clearance collapses and the UA vertical-centering algorithm clips the top glyph. The fix is structural — replace `<input>` with `contenteditable` — not cosmetic. No combination of `padding-top`, `line-height`, or `box-sizing` applied to the `<input>` itself will resolve the clip, because those properties affect the box boundary, not the browser-native text rendering origin inside it.
